---
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Header from "../components/sections/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/sections/Footer.astro";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en" data-theme="dark" class="dark">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title="The 19 - Order of the 19th" description="Meet the legendary members who shaped the game and those who carry the tradition forward." />
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-7xl px-4 py-12">
      
 <!-- THE HEAD OF THE ORDER - Hero Section -->
<section class="mb-20 text-center">
  <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold mb-6 text-[color:var(--accent)]">
    The Head of the Order
  </h1>
  <p class="text-xl mb-12 text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    Our eternal founder, whose vision and passion laid the foundation for all who follow
  </p>
  
  <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-8 hover:shadow-xl transition-shadow">
    <div class="w-48 h-48 mx-auto mb-6 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
      <img src="/images/man1800.png" alt="Master Liang" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
    </div>
    
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Master Liang</h2>
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-4">St Andrews, Scotland • 1524–1590</p>
    <p class="text-lg mb-4 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ Old Course at St Andrews</p>
    
    <blockquote class="text-xl italic my-6 px-4 border-l-4 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
      "I served drinks before I served wisdom."
    </blockquote>
    
    <p class="text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-6">
      In his late twenties, Master Liang pushed a humble food cart to the edge of the Old Course
      and quietly turned thirsty golfers into the first members of an invisible club.
    </p>
    
    <a href="/blog" class="inline-block px-6 py-3 bg-[color:var(--accent)] !text-white rounded-md hover:opacity-90 transition-opacity">
      Read His Legend →
    </a>
  </div>
</section>


      <!-- THE FRONT NINE -->
      <section class="mb-20">
        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-[color:var(--accent)]">The Front Nine</h2>
          <p class="text-xl text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] max-w-3xl mx-auto">
            Legends Who Shaped the Game
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
          <!-- Member 1 -->
         <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
  <div class="w-32 h-32 mx-auto mb-4 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
    <img src="/images/man1950.png" alt="Brother MacLaing" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
  </div>
  <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Brother MacLaing</h3>
  <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-3">St Andrews, Scotland • c. 1720–1779</p>
  <p class="text-sm mb-3 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ Leith Links</p>
  <blockquote class="text-sm italic my-4 px-3 border-l-2 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
    "A round is not finished until a man has shared it in good company."
  </blockquote>
  <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-4">
    A quiet trader’s son who carried Master Liang’s family custom east to Leith, Brother MacLaing became the discreet bridge between taverns, new clubs and those who chose to finish their round properly at an unseen 19th.
  </p>
  <a href="/blog" class="text-[color:var(--accent)] hover:underline text-sm">
    Read Their Legend →
  </a>
</div>

          <!-- Member 2 -->
          <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
            <div class="w-32 h-32 mx-auto mb-4 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
              <img src="/images/man1950.png" alt="Brother Calder" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Brother Calder</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-3">St Andrews, Scotland • c. 1714–1781</p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ The Old Course, St Andrews</p>
            <blockquote class="text-sm italic my-4 px-3 border-l-2 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
              "Eighteen holes mark the score, but the nineteenth reveals the player."
            </blockquote>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-4">
              Fascinated by how golfers moved across the Old Course and gathered after play, Brother Calder stood witness when it was cut to eighteen holes and began sketching a hidden nineteenth in his mind – a brotherhood without walls for those who stayed to share the day.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog" class="text-[color:var(--accent)] hover:underline text-sm">
              Read Their Legend →
            </a>
          </div>

          <!-- Member 3 -->
          <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
            <div class="w-32 h-32 mx-auto mb-4 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
              <img src="/images/man1950.png" alt="Brother Rowan" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Brother Rowan</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-3">Edinburgh, Scotland • c. 1768–1836</p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ Bruntsfield Links & Musselburgh Links</p>
            <blockquote class="text-sm italic my-4 px-3 border-l-2 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
              "Wherever a golfer ends his day, there should be one door that opens a little easier for him."
            </blockquote>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-4">
              A commercial traveller with a modest game but an excellent memory, Brother Rowan carried the quiet customs of MacLaing and Calder out of St Andrews and Leith and into the taverns and golf houses of Edinburgh and Musselburgh, recruiting innkeepers into an informal nineteenth‑hole network of stories, favours and information.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog" class="text-[color:var(--accent)] hover:underline text-sm">
              Read Their Legend →
            </a>
          </div>

          <!-- Member 4 -->
          <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
            <div class="w-32 h-32 mx-auto mb-4 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
              <img src="/images/lady1950.png" alt="Sister Morag Fisher" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
            </div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Sister Morag</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-3">Fisherrow, Musselburgh • c. 1778–1842</p>
            <p class="text-sm mb-3 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ Musselburgh Links</p>
            <blockquote class="text-sm italic my-4 px-3 border-l-2 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
              "I carried fish and stories on the same back, and both found good tables in the end."
            </blockquote>
            <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-4">
              A formidable Musselburgh fishwife who played golf on her days off and walked miles with a creel on her back, Sister Morag became the first woman of the Order, carrying its spirit along the coast in the gossip and trade of the fishing boats and binding the nineteenth hole to smoky kitchens, harbour taverns and the rough laughter of her own.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog" class="text-[color:var(--accent)] hover:underline text-sm">
              Read Their Legend →
            </a>
           </div>

            <!-- Member 5 -->
            <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
              <div class="w-32 h-32 mx-auto mb-4 rounded-full overflow-hidden">
                <img src="/images/man1950.png" alt="Brother Shaw" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
              </div>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Brother Shaw</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text-secondary)] mb-3">Greenwich, England • c. 1575–1645</p>
              <p class="text-sm mb-3 text-[color:var(--accent)]">⛳ Royal Blackheath Golf Club</p>
              <blockquote class="text-sm italic my-4 px-3 border-l-2 border-[color:var(--accent)]">
                "A game without a gathering is only half played."
              </blockquote>
              <p class="text-sm text-[color:var(--color-text)] mb-4">
                A river man moving between Greenwich taverns and the royal ground on the heath, Brother Shaw carried the quiet customs of the 19th hole from Scottish links into England’s first true golfing society, ensuring every round above London ended within sight of the Thames.
              </p>
              <a href="/blog" class="text-[color:var(--accent)] hover:underline text-sm">
                Read Their Legend →
              </a>
            </div>

            <!-- Member 6 -->
            <div class="bg-[color:var(--color-card)] border border-[color:var(--color-border)] rounded-lg p-6 hover:shadow-xl hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all">
